628
00:47:39,920 --> 00:47:44,136
"Is Final Fantasy VII a Radical Left-Wing
Game?"

629
00:47:44,160 --> 00:47:50,055
But before we put our stamp on the question once and
for all, I think it's worth noting a couple of things:

630
00:47:50,079 --> 00:47:54,456
First, a handful of you, including my
Developmental Editor Elizabeth

631
00:47:54,480 --> 00:47:58,696
might be annoyed that I spent a lot of
time talking about the "Content" of Final

632
00:47:58,720 --> 00:48:03,496
Fantasy VII without even touching the
"Form" of Final Fantasy VII.

633
00:48:03,520 --> 00:48:06,856
To quote Elizabeth's notes on this video:

634
00:48:06,880 --> 00:48:10,936
"I think part of the analysis of a work
of art's politics is not just its content

635
00:48:10,960 --> 00:48:14,376
[what the game is about, the issues it
deals with, what the plot and characters

636
00:48:14,400 --> 00:48:19,575
show about the politics of the work, etc.]
but its form. For instance, what kind of

637
00:48:19,599 --> 00:48:23,656
narrative it is, how does its genre
influence the story being told, what kind

638
00:48:23,680 --> 00:48:27,976
of interactions does it create with its
audience, what kind of 'subject' interacts

639
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:33,176
with it and interprets it and how;
also who produces it, how it's produced

640
00:48:33,200 --> 00:48:38,295
why societies turn to certain kinds of art
(such as video games) at certain times."

641
00:48:38,319 --> 00:48:43,016
The relationship of "Form" and "Content"
comes out of the writings of G. W. F. Hegel

642
00:48:43,040 --> 00:48:47,176
and Marxist thinkers like Theodor
Adorno, and it's definitely something i

643
00:48:47,200 --> 00:48:50,856
could stand to learn more about.
I'm leaving this as an open thread for

644
00:48:50,880 --> 00:48:56,136
folks to discuss and I might pick it
back up for a new video in the future.

645
00:48:56,160 --> 00:49:01,016
Second, let's be mindful of our tendency
as left-wing consumers and critics to

646
00:49:01,040 --> 00:49:05,575
impute certain political conclusions to
works of art that we enjoy.

647
00:49:05,599 --> 00:49:09,815
Take the statement by English professor
Nicola Nixon:

648
00:49:09,839 --> 00:49:14,055
"The conflation of aesthetic appreciation
and good politics surfaces in certain

649
00:49:14,079 --> 00:49:18,456
critics as a form of leftist wish
fulfillment... in other words, if one likes

650
00:49:18,480 --> 00:49:25,176
the fiction, it must necessarily involve the
articulation of a perceptible, revolutionary project."

651
00:49:25,200 --> 00:49:29,656
Definitely a mood. I often have to stop
myself from running too wild with my

652
00:49:29,680 --> 00:49:32,936
left-wing wish fulfillment when I
brainstorm and write up outlines for my

653
00:49:32,960 --> 00:49:37,656
videos. As a leftist, I think it's fun to
recognize and appreciate radical

654
00:49:37,680 --> 00:49:42,136
left-wing elements in a work, whether
it's anti-capitalist themes, rhetoric

655
00:49:42,160 --> 00:49:47,896
about things like "workers' rights," and
relations that mirror relations we see in history.

656
00:49:47,920 --> 00:49:51,896
I think I would conclude that Final
Fantasy VII doesn't use its radical

657
00:49:51,920 --> 00:49:58,535
left-wing elements as set dressing, but makes those
elements crucial to the existence of its world:

658
00:49:58,559 --> 00:50:03,416
look towards Midgar, the Shinra Company,
and Avalanche as examples.

659
00:50:03,440 --> 00:50:06,216
That said, having reviewed the body of
evidence,

660
00:50:06,240 --> 00:50:14,776
I don't think Final Fantasy VII - the original, Remake Part
